<p id="p0355">This integral equation is the Lippmann-Schwinger equation. It is identical to the original Schrödinger 
 <xref rid="fd20" ref-type="disp-formula">Eq. (20)</xref> or 
 <xref rid="fd44" ref-type="disp-formula">(44)</xref> (this can be easily verified by acting the operator 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M170" altimg="si144.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mo stretchy="true">(</mo>
     <mrow>
      <mtext>H</mtext>
      <mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mover accent="true">
        <mi>U</mi>
        <mo>˜</mo>
       </mover>
      </mrow>
      <mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mo>
      <msub>
       <mrow>
        <mi>E</mi>
       </mrow>
       <mrow>
        <mtext>H</mtext>
       </mrow>
      </msub>
     </mrow>
     <mo stretchy="true">)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>on the left and right sides of the equation and taking into account 
 <xref rid="fd45" ref-type="disp-formula">Eq. (45)</xref>). We rewrite the Lippmann-Schwinger equation (
 <xref rid="fd51" ref-type="disp-formula">Eq. (51)</xref>) in the symbolic form
 <disp-formula id="fd52">
  <label>(52)</label>
  <math id="M171" altimg="si149.svg" alttext="Equation 52.">
   <mrow>
    <mi>Ψ</mi>
    <mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mo>
    <mrow>
     <mover accent="true">
      <mi>Ψ</mi>
      <mo>˜</mo>
     </mover>
    </mrow>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak">+</mo>
    <mi>G</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mover accent="true">
      <mi>U</mi>
      <mo>˜</mo>
     </mover>
    </mrow>
    <mi>Ψ</mi>
    <mtext>.</mtext>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>
</p>
